Relatives of those killed in a fire at a German-owned textile factory in the Baldia area protested to demand a lump sum compensation from the company.
The Shia Ulema Council Karachi Chapter protested and marched in the Jamshed area of Karachi against the Sehwan shrine bombing.
Relatives of a man who died of hepatitis protested in Kandiaro and accused doctors of negligence.
Protests and rallies were held in different parts of Karachi to protest the recent Sehwan shrine bombing.
Jamaat Ulema Pakistan activists staged a rally in Liaquatabad over the Sehwan shrine bombing.

Police and Orangi Town residents clashed during a protest demonstration against insecuring insecurity in the area. Nearly a dozen protesters were injured during the incident as police fired tear gas and used aerial firing to disperse them. One of those injured later died. 15 people were also later arrested, and cases registered against 250.
The Sindh Civil Society Forum held a march in Sehwan in protest against the Sehewan shrine bombing.
Activists of the SUC, SBT and QAT protested at the Shikarpur press club against the Sehwan shrine bombing.
62 people were arrested in different parts of Quetta in a crackdown following the Sehwan shrine bombing.
Unidentified gunmen on motorcycles shot and killed the leader of JUI-F's Charsadda chapter.

column23: The Frontier Post; Daily Pakistan Today
column24: At least 15 people were injured in a cracker blast at the Abdul Wahab Shah Jeelani flyover. The JSMM is suspected by police as being behind the attack, and several JSMM leaders and workers were arrested.

At least 5 students were injured, most seriously, as some unidentified assailants attacked a group of QAU students from the Quaidian Students Federation. The attackers were suspected as having been members of a fringe religious party.

5 people were injured in a firing incident at the NADRA office in Quetta. It is not clear what led to the violence. The gunfight was between some unidentified assailants and some guards at the NADRA building.
4 suspected militants were killed and dozens of suspects arrested on Feb.20 in an ongoing crackdown on militants in Sindh and Lahore following the Sehwan shrine bombing.
4 suspected militants were killed and dozens of suspects arrested on Feb.20 in an ongoing crackdown on militants in Sindh and Lahore following the Sehwan shrine bombing.
4 TTP militant commanders were killed in a military operation in FR Tank.
Unidentified armed assailants on motorcycles opened fire on a Levies force member on duty in the Noshki area.
2 people were injured by an IED in the Lehri area.
12 suspected TTP militants were killed and several others injured in new airstrikes on the Wucha Bibi area of NWA.
Activists of the Anjuman Qalandari protested in the Dadu area against the Sehwan shrine bombing.

Large numbers of political party activists and workers disrupted traffic between Dera Murad Jamali and Jacobabad to protest against the Uch power plant authorities for allegedly not supplying power to the Nasirabad district.
After the body of a missing child was found, the child's relatives protested in Gujranwala to demand an investigation.
Relatives of a missing youth leader Fayaz Dahri protested in the Hingorja area for his recovery.
Civil society activists staged a demo at the National Press Club against the Sehwan shrine bombing and other militant attacks in the country.
Activists of different political, social and religious parties protested in Khairpur against the Sehwan shrine bombing.
Residents of the village of Khan Mohammad Shahani protested over the murder of a youth in their area and demanded the arrest of those responsible.
Angry villagers from the Lakki Marwat area disrupted a council meeting to protest against power disconnections in their areas.
Employees of the Law Department protested outside the sessions court in Larkana to demand promotions and salary increases.
Lower staff of the Education Department protested in favour of their demands in Sujawal.
200 suspected militants were arrested in Tank and Swabi district on Feb.20.
200 suspected militants were arrested in Tank and Swabi district on Feb.20.
The residence of the facilitator of the Lahore protest bombing was demolished by Pakistani security forces in Lahore, in the Bhagatpura area.

At least 8 people were killed, including a lawyer, 3 bombers and 4 police personnel, and 20 others injured when multiple suicide bombers hit a sessions court in the Tangi area of Charsadda district. The attackers attempted to enter the court premises, opening fire and throwing grenades, and detonated themselves after security forces opened fire. JuA claimed the attack, and the attackers were reported to be Uzbek nationals.
5 militants were killed and several hideouts destroyed in airstrikes by the military on the Rajgal locality of Khyber Agency.
3 FC personnel were injured in a roadsibe bomb on Sakran Road near Noorani Hotel in Hub.
2 people were killed and one seriously injured when their motorcycle hit a landmine in the Dera Bugti area.

JuD activists staged a nation-wide protest and threatened a long march to demand the release of their leader who is under house arrest in connection with the 2008 Mumbai attack. Protests were held in Lahore at Choburji Chowk and in Karachi at the press club in Saddar Town, as well as Sialkot, Islamabad, Multan, Gujranwala, Bahawalnagar, Hyderabad, Faisalabad, Kasur, Quetta, Peshawar, Muzaffarabad, Kotli and Rawalakot.
Rickshaw drivers protested at the Lorry Adda in Daska against traffic police who they allege have been demanding bribes.
Students of the Indus International Institute protested and rallied against the institute's management over the issuance of alleged fake degrees to students.

Players of the Hyderi Football Club protested against the relevant authorities over the release of sewage water on the Mumtaz Ground.
Leaders of seven industries and town associations in Karachi held a token protest at the premises of the PHMA House over SEPA notices.
Workers and officer-bearers of JI's youth wing in Mirpurkhas protested against a lack of inspections fort he city's railways.
Some workers of Sweet Home Pakistan protested against an in-charge of Baitul Mal Saleem Baloch for allegedly stealing their mobile phones and mistreating them.
Pak-Turk teaching staff and parents protested outside the Karachi press club against the CTD and Punjab police for allegedly harassing the chairman of the Pak-Turk School Foundation.
Unidentified assailants threw a grenade at the Election Commission's office in Turbat. No casualties reported.
A BLF commander was killed and 6 others arrested by security forces in the Dashat Crossing area of Kech district.
Civil society activists, political leaders and lawyers held a peace march in Charsadda against recent bombings in the district.
Scores of people blocked traffic on the bus stand road and railway track at Gojra over the alleged killing of a trader by robbers.
Punjab Livestock Employees Association protested to demand the government upgrade their service structure outside their offices in Gulberg, Lahore.
The relatives of a young boy protested outside the Karachi press club after he died, alleging medical negligence.
Relatives of 2 murdered brothers protested in the Gohadpur area of Sialkot to demand action.
Livestock owners protested again in Sibi over the delay of a local livestock festival. They went on strike and marched through Sibi.
Teachers protested on the Lower Mall Rd in Lahore to demand the government keep its promises to them.
A Pakistani soldier was injured when an unidentified militant fired across the border from Afghanistan in the Mangrotia locality of SWA.
Hundreds of residents of towns around Dadu protested and blocked traffic to demand the restoration of power supplies to their localities and against HESCO officials.
Following a sectarian attack in Prawa tehsil of Dera Ismail Khan district, relatives of those killed protested and demanded the arrest of those responsible.
Teachers of different government schools from Mehran's Teachers Colony protested against the sale of the residential colony.
Members of the Hindu community protested against the occupation of religious places, including temples, in the Khairpur area.
Afghan nationals stranded in Pakistan protested outside the Landi Kotal press club to demand the reopening of the Torkham border crossing.
Members of the Municipal Employees Union in Larkana protested to demand their salaries.
Employees of the local education department protested and marched in Nawabshah to draw attention to their demands.

Members of the JI's FATA chapter protested and staged a sit-in outside the governor's house in Peshawar against the exclusion of the FATA reforms from the cabinet's agenda and to demand the FCR be abolished.

A clash broke out between two PML-N groups when supporters of the municipal committee chairman allegedly attacked a petrol pump owner. The other PML-N activists came to the owner's defense, leading to the fight.
3 people were killed in an alleged sectarian attack in the Prawa tehsil of Dera Ismail Khan district.
People in the Arkari area protested over the lack of infrastructure in their area, as well as over blocked roads.
Members of the Young Doctors Association in Hyderabad and Jamshoro went on strike and protested to demand attention to their grievances.

Contract-based teachers of the NCHD protested in favour of their demands.
Sacked employees of the Municipal Corporation Larkana protested outside the Larkana press club to draw attention to their demands.
JUI-F activists protested outside the Larkana press club against corruption and terrorism.
Residents of Siddiqui colony in Larkana protested against the SEPCO authorities for disconnecting their power supplies.
Scores of government contractors held a demo in front of the provicinial highway division in Mirpurkhas over the alleged awarding of contractors based on bribery.
55 secretaries of union councils along with lower staff employees protested outside the Mirpurkhas press club to draw attention to their grievances.
Employees of the Prosecution Department boycotted court proceedings and staged a protest outside the local court in Moro to demand attention to their grievances.
An organization of workers from various political parties held a protest demo outside the Peshawar press club against the government.
2 suspected robbers were assaulted by an angry mob in Orangi town before being handed over to police.

12 people were injured in alleged firing by a PML-N MPA and his guard on a protest led by Anjuman-e-Tajran against the alleged indecent behaviour of the PML-N MPA. Another report said the incident occurred over a property dispute.

Police used water cannons and tear gas to disperse protesters in Colombo Fort, on Wednesday. The protestors are agitating a government move to ender into an agreement with China on the development of the Hambantota port. The protest was organized by the Federation of Trade Unions to Protect Harbors.

On Thursday, over 2,000 university students are currently marching into Colombo Fort in protest of the Court of Appeal ruling on the SAITM medical degree. The protesting university students are demanding the closure of the South Asian Institute of Technology and Medicine (SAITM) on the basis that the court order would lead to the privatization of the country's education system. The protest march into Colombo Fort has caused heavy traffic on the roads.
On Friday, a protest by Ceylon Electricity Board (CEB) workers, in front of the CEB in Colombo Fort has caused traffic in Colombo. The protestors are asking that salary anomalies are rectified.

On Tuesday, the areas surrounding Ward Place and Town Hall in Colombo were hampered with traffic owing to a protest by the Inter University Trade Union. The IUTU is protesting salary payment irregularities outside the University Grants Commission on Ward Place.

In Batticaloa, a Tamil Makkal Peravai demonstration, initiated by North Province Chief Minister C.V. Wigneswaran was held near the Kalladi clock tower on Friday. The protestors are demanding that lands occupied by the military are restored, their missing are found, that the Tamil-Hindu culture in the North and East is left undisturbed and that the Northern and Southern parts of the country are united
On Wednesday, the Lotus road in Colombo Fort was temporarily closed due to a protest by textile workers. The protest against canceling pension has hampered traffic in the area.

More than a thousand Peradeniya University students on Thursday launched a protest march to Colombo urging the government to take over the Malambe private medical college also known as SAITM. They set out on their march after an hour's protest in the Kandy town.

Wimalraj Nesan, Director at the Land Reforms Commission (LRC) at the Batticaloa District Secretariat was injured in a shooting on Wednesday. He was shot at by two unidentified gunmen who had arrived on a motorcycle at Kalawanchikudy.
Muslim students staged rallies across the southern provinces to demand self-determination, call for peace, and mark the shooting deaths of three Muslim children three years ago.

About 300 airport workers at Suvarnabhumi airport went on strike, gathering in front of a security management office to voice their demands. Their demands included an increase in base salary, overtime rates, and travel benefits.
Seven soldiers were injured by an explosion in their pick up truck while they were traveling back to their base in Aranyaprathet district. The cause of the explosion was unknown.

Arsonists attacked two rock quarries in Ban Lidon village on Highway 409 in Muang Yala. The armed men forced guards to lie face down at gunpoint, and then placed pieces of cloth soaked with petrol around wheels of vehicles and the building. At the same time, a separate group of arsonists did the same thing at a quarry about 300 meters away. Police were investigating whether the attack was related to the insurgency.
The chairman of a tambon administration organization was killed by gunmen in Pate village in tambon Piya Mumang. He had been an influential figure in the district.

Four men were injured a roadside bomb blast in Chanae district as they were on their way to go hunt wild boar. The bomb, planted near a power pole, went off as their pick up truck passed by. Police blamed insurgents for the attack.
A soldier providing protection for teachers near Moo 1 village in tambon Buere was wounded by a bomb detonation.

100 residents from Lat Phrao gathered at the Administrative Court in Bangkok to issue an injunction against the Bangkok Metropolitan Administration for demolishing several pavilions on Lat Phrao's grounds.

Arsonists attacked a construction company in Muang district in the middle of the night. The company, Yala Construction Company, is on Highway 409 in tambon Lidon. Some of the property was damaged. Police were investigating.

Environmental groups protested for several days in Bangkok to oppose the Prime Minister's decision to proceed with a coal-power plant in Krabi. The activists protested outside Government House until the government agreed to restart an inquiry into the issue.

A man was shot dead while returning home on a motorcycle in Nong Chik district by an attacker hiding on the road side.

Protesting monks gathered in Dhammakaya Temple for several days to urge the junta to reverse an order sealing off the compound. Nearly 4,000 police were stationed around the temple, but had been instructed not to use violence or weapons to remove the protesters.

Two policemen, three monks and a woman were injured in a scuffle as monks were trying to enter a temple, the site of an ongoing protest. The monks were blocked by police, resulting in the two groups pushing and shoving for nearly twenty minutes.

A community group blocked the entrance to a gold mine in Wang Saphung district for several days as part of their protest against illegal mining. The group suspects that the mining is occurring illegally.

Cambodian merchants protested against a huge increase in import duty on fish by Thai authorities. The protesters, about 100 of them, piled fish in the center of the Thai-Cambodian Friendship bridge, blocking traffic.

About 200 protesters blocked the demolition of two homes in Soi Mukdee, in Phuket's Muang district. Many residents in this area have been forcefully evicted recently.

Seven unidentified militants raided the office of a tambon administration organization in Tak Bai district, tying up employees and setting fire to the office building and an emergency rescue vehicle before fleeing with a pick-up truck.

Thai workers were building a wall on the Thai side of the Moei River to prevent soil erosion in Mae Sot district when they were attacked from across the river by members of Myanmar's Border Guard Force, who were doing so in order to express opposition to the embankment wall being built.
